All functions in R have at least 3 things:

-A **name** we pick this and use it to call the function. - Input **arguments**, there can be multiple comma separated inputs ot the function - The **body**, lines of R code that do the work of the function

Our first wee function:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
add<-function(x, y=1) {
  x+y
}
```
:::


Lets test our function


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
add(c(1,2,3), y=10)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 11 12 13
```


:::
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
add(10,100)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 110
```


:::
:::


## A second function

Let's try something more interesting. Make a sequence generation tool.

The `sample()` function could be useful here.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
sample(1:10, size= 3)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 2 3 8
```


:::
:::


change this to work with the nucleotides A C G and T


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
n<-c("A","C","T","G")
sample(n, size=5, replace = TRUE)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "C" "A" "G" "T" "G"
```


:::
:::


TUrn this snippet into a function that returns a user specified length dna sequence. Let's call it `generate_dna()`


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna<-function(len=10, fasta=FALSE) {
  n<-c("A","C","T","G")
  v<- sample(n, size=len, replace = TRUE)

  # Make a single element vector
  s<-paste(v, collapse="")

  cat("Well done you!")

  if(fasta) {
 return(s)    
  }else{
    return(v)
  }
}
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna(5)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
Well done you!
```


:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "T" "G" "A" "A" "A"
```


:::
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
s<-generate_dna(15)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
Well done you!
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
s
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
